# NOTE: Keep this list short (~8 entries). Remove old ones as new ones land.
CHANGELOG = [
    "b446: mechanical dead-code sweep, no behaviour change. Removed 52 f-strings that had no placeholders (f\"...\" -> \"...\"), 59 unused local variables, and one unreachable block in combat.py (a 'Your Memorized Spells:' listing sat after an unconditional return inside the cmd=='init' branch, so it could never run). Net ~75 lines gone across 9 files. Verified by a 200-turn smart playtest whose full log is byte-identical to the pre-change baseline, plus clean runs on seeds 1/7/42. Import-star re-exports were deliberately left untouched. First of a multi-step cleanup pass.",
    "b445: moved the dev-only headless playtest harness + report out of the wizardscavern package into a new top-level playtest_tools/ package, so Briefcase (sources = [\"wizardscavern\"]) no longer bundles ~500KB of test-only code into the APK. No game module imports these at runtime -- they are leaf dev tools -- but living inside the package meant every player install shipped them. Rewrote all 49 game-module imports from relative to absolute (from wizardscavern.X), including the dozens of lazy in-function imports, not just the top-level ones; the sibling playtest_report import stays relative since both files moved together. Invocation changes to python -m playtest_tools.playtest_harness; updated the playtester agent, deploy script, HANDOFF and docs index to match. Verified by a 400-turn smart/playtest-mode run plus report generation with zero tracebacks and no import errors.",
    "b444: the lantern now reveals a FILLED CIRCLE of light that grows as you upgrade it, instead of the thin four-direction cross. The light is a line-of-sight disc -- it fills every open tile within range but is blocked by walls, so it never leaks around corners into rooms you haven't reached (the exact bug that retired the old disc and forced the cross stopgap; this version raycasts each tile via Bresenham to fix it). Radius scales with the Scroll of Lantern Upgrade: base 3, +2 per upgrade (3 / 5 / 7 tiles at +0 / +1 / +2), so a maxed lantern lights ~148 tiles per fire vs 28 at base. The base light_radius dropped 7 -> 3 across the lantern template, vendor stock, starter pack, and save-load default to keep early-game fog tension. The upgrade scroll now reports the new radius, both reveal call-sites (inventory use + the 'l' quick-use hotkey) share one helper so they can't drift apart, and _create_item_copy no longer silently resets a lantern's upgrade_level (which would have wiped your upgrades and shrunk the light back to base).",
    "b443: unified Lantern Fuel canister strength to 20 everywhere. The shop/utility-template canister (item_templates.py) only restored 10 -- half what chest drops, vendor stock, and the item's own class default give (20) -- so buying fuel from a vendor was a stealthily worse deal than finding it in a chest. Bumped it to 20, and fixed the save-load fallback default (25 -> 20) so a canister from an old save deserializes to the canonical value. Also corrected stale playtest-harness docs/comments that still described canisters as +10 (the smart policy keeps its conservative *10 reserve estimate intentionally -- now annotated as a caution margin, not a bug) and fixed a comment claiming the lantern reveal radius was upgrade_level+1 when it's actually light_radius+upgrade_level.",
    "b442: fixed a lantern refuel bug that wiped your whole Lantern Fuel stack. The quick-use 'l' hotkey has two refuel paths: one for when fuel drains mid-use, and one for when you press 'l' with the lantern already at 0 fuel. The b370 stack-wipe fix only landed in the first path (and in items.py); the second still carried the old bug -- it restored a hardcoded +10 (ignoring the canister's real fuel_restore_amount of 20) and called remove_item(name), which drops the ENTIRE LanternFuel stack regardless of count. So an empty lantern + a fresh stack of canisters lost the whole stack on one refuel and only gained 10 fuel. Now mirrors the corrected pattern: uses fuel_restore_amount and decrements count by one. Reachable any time the lantern hit 0 with no fuel on hand, then you later picked up canisters.",
    "b441: restyled the UI chips (CRAFT/SPELLS/JOURNAL/QUIT/CLOSE action chips, the All/Use/Equip/Eat filter tabs, combat/lantern/stairs HUD chips, and the unequip chip) from modern glossy pills to a retro+dungeon 'hybrid' look: square-ish 3px corners, a 2px pixel bevel (light top-left / dark bottom-right inset shadow) over a carved-stone gradient fill, engraved text (dark text-shadow), and the 8-bit Press Start 2P typeface. The font is bundled inline as a base64 woff2 @font-face (OFL-licensed latin subset, ~4.7KB) so it renders offline in the APK webview with no network fetch. Colour identities are preserved (SPELLS=arcane purple, QUIT/CLOSE/FLEE=danger rust, ATTACK=red, LANTERN=gold, STAIRS/active-filter=green) but rendered as muted stone slabs with dark carved borders. Press feedback flips the bevel inward (pushed-in) with a brightness pop; the selected filter tab reads as depressed. Body text stays Courier New -- only the chips change.",
    "b440: promoted the 6 reserve potion sprites (P002/P006/P013/P018/P021/P104) into the in-game pool, taking it from 87 to 93. With b439's collision-free assignment that drops worst-case in-session potion sprite reuse from 9 to just 4 (96 distinct potion types vs 93 sprites -- the remaining overlap is the unavoidable pigeonhole floor plus one duplicate-named template). The reserve renders sat on solid-black backgrounds (they never went through the b433-b439 Gemini transparency pass), so each was background-removed first via a corner flood-fill alpha cut -- connected near-black border pixels are made transparent while the bottles' closed dark outlines keep their interior liquid intact -- plus a 1px dark-edge feather so no black halo rings them on the dark UI panels. Re-encoded RGBA WebP q80 to match the pool, injected with in-game potion schema; sprites/potions.py, the package snippet, and potions_library.json (6 moved reserve->chosen) all kept in sync.",
    "b439: stopped potions/scrolls reusing sprites within a game. The cryptic icon picker hashed each per-game appearance name straight into the sprite pool with `pid = pool[hash(name) % len(pool)]` -- birthday-paradox clustering meant potions touched only 57 of 87 sprites, with 39 distinct potions doubled (or up to 5x) onto a shared icon, and scrolls collided 7 times despite a 42-sprite pool for 26 types. Replaced the modulo hash with a collision-free assignment (sprites/identifiables.py): each distinct appearance is walked onto a per-game-shuffled pool permutation, so no two appearances share a sprite until the pool is genuinely exhausted -- potions drop to the pigeonhole minimum (9 unavoidable, 96 types vs 87 sprites), scrolls to zero. The permutation is seeded off the per-game cryptic pairing, so the identification minigame still randomises each potion's look per game while keeping it stable (and consistent before/after ID) within a run. Assignment is cached and rebuilt only when a new game reshuffles the mapping. Spells were already collision-free via their hand-authored named map -- left untouched.",
]

